So if you call `ret = waitpid(pid, &amp;exitstat, WNOHANG)`, then the command will return even if the child did not exit. Hence you need to look at the returned value `ret` to see if the function was successful and then the value of `exitstat` to see if the child has exited (either by returning from the `main()` function or due to a signal):
```
if(ret &gt;= 0)
{
    if(WIFEXITED(exitstat) || WIFSIGNALED(exitstat))
    {
        printf(&quot;Child ended\n&quot;);
    }
}
else
{
    printf(&quot;Error!\n&quot;);
}
```
Note:

1. In some cases, you may also want to check `WIFSTOPPED(exitstat)`. See [waitpid(2)](https://linux.die.net/man/2/waitpid) for details.

2. In case of error, you may check [errno](http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/errno.3.html) for further information about what went wrong.

